abstract.value: Cleveland Robinson (1914-1995) was an African American trade union leader and civil rights activist who served as Secretary-Treasurer of the United Auto Workers of America, District 65, from 1952-1992. The collection contains correspondence, miscellaneous documents, ephemera and clippings.

p.value: Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date; Cleveland Robinson Papers; WAG 006.001; box number; folder number; <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

Donated by the United Automobile, Aircraft, and Vehicle Workers of America. District 65, in 1992, at the time of Cleveland Robinson's retirement and the dissolution of District 65 into ten separate locals within the UAW. The accession number associated with this gift is 1992.005.

His first wife was Sue Eliza Robinson, a department store worker and member of District 65; and they had two sons and a daughter. After her death in 1976 he married again, Doreen McPherson Robinson. He suffered severely from glaucoma for many years, and was considered legally blind by 1970; but his level of commitment and activity was in no way impaired by this disability. He never lost touch with his Jamaican origins and traveled to the island often, keeping up a keen interest in a number of Jamaican-American political, cultural and fraternal organizations. Cleveland Robinson died of kidney failure in New York City in August 1995.

Series 1. UAW, District 65 Files, 1956-1992, includes a wide range of documentation of every aspect of union affairs: organizing files, grievances, bargaining records, financial reports, benefits files, legal records, and officers' and members' correspondence. Also documented are the union's extensive educational and cultural programs, and its special interest in organizing in the South. Series 2. General and Political Files, 1960-1992, provides a detailed picture of Robinson's political interests and affiliations. Included are records of his involvement in African affairs, anti-apartheid campaigns, the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists, the King Center in Atlanta, New York City and state human rights and civil rights commissions, and a wide range of smaller campaigns and organizations. Also included is his correspondence with leading political and cultural figures, trade unionists, and personal friends, as well as letters from ordinary workers, both in the U.S. and in Jamaica.
